But these are some of the ways
in which we improve the

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:50.610
navigation as well as separate
out the concept of navigation

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:53.380
from actions such as filter.

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:55.603
With that should we move on to
design consistency, Nick?

00:16:55.603 --> 00:16:57.000
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah, let's.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:57.895
ROMAN NURIK: All right.

00:16:57.895 --> 00:17:00.430
NICK BUTCHER: So this is a topic
that we've been chewing

00:17:00.430 --> 00:17:01.460
on for a little while.

00:17:01.460 --> 00:17:03.910
And I think it's something that
lot of people struggle

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:04.750
with out there.

00:17:04.750 --> 00:17:08.230
And understanding how do you
design with Android, how do

00:17:08.230 --> 00:17:11.950
you have that consistent with
the rest of your brand and

00:17:11.950 --> 00:17:14.730
applications and so
on out there.

00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:17.530
So when we talk about
consistency, there's a few

00:17:17.530 --> 00:17:21.000
dimensions we want to really
define and really dig into.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.319
The first one is that
cross platform.

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:26.460
So obviously there's a bunch of
different OS platforms out

00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:29.270
there which you, your
application and your service,

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:31.270
whatever it might be, probably
wants to be present on.

00:17:31.270 --> 00:17:34.350
So there's got to be an element
of consistency so

00:17:34.350 --> 00:17:37.390
users know how to use your
application across these.

00:17:37.390 --> 00:17:39.550
The next dimension
we think about is

00:17:39.550 --> 00:17:40.960
your branding, really.

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:43.960
So even if you're running on all
these different platforms,

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:46.540
you want to be recognizable as
the same service, and how do

00:17:46.540 --> 00:17:48.850
you achieve that?

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:50.440
And the next dimension that you
think about, so when we're

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:54.820
talking specifically about
Android, Android obviously has

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:57.726
its own look and feel, its own
interaction patterns and so

00:17:57.726 --> 00:18:00.880
forth, kind of wrapped up in the
Holo design language and

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:03.300
the Android design patterns.

00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:07.530
So how do you reconcile being
consistent with that?

00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:10.320
So there's a lot of confusion
and choice out there.

00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:14.220
So to tackle those, we break
it down into three design

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:14.440
disciplines.

00:18:14.440 --> 00:18:17.350
We're going to talk individually
about your

00:18:17.350 --> 00:18:19.810
information design, your
interaction design, and your

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:21.330
visual design.

00:18:21.330 --> 00:18:24.250
And how to be consistent
with those.

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:28.920
So the first step, the
information design.

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:32.190
Android or the Holographic, the
Holo design, which really

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:35.700
isn't going to dictate to you
or tell you anything here.

00:18:35.700 --> 00:18:38.970
There's nothing stopping
you from using the same

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:41.290
information architecture that
you used, say, if you already

00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:44.130
have a web property or
a different platform.

00:18:44.130 --> 00:18:46.560
This is all down to
your application.

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:48.930
I think this just comes down to
good design, where you want

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:52.290
to sit down and map out what the
base entities are in the

00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:55.290
information architecture
of your application.

00:18:55.290 --> 00:18:57.220
But Android isn't going to
influence this at all.

00:18:57.220 --> 00:18:59.140
So this is all on you.

00:18:59.140 --> 00:19:01.540
On [INAUDIBLE] slider map
we've put together here.

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:04.220
ROMAN NURIK: I guess the point
I wanted to make here is that

00:19:04.220 --> 00:19:08.120
the information design, or
information architecture,

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:10.860
especially for apps that have an
existing, potentially very

00:19:10.860 --> 00:19:15.110
large user base or existing
property on the web or on

00:19:15.110 --> 00:19:16.580
other mobile platforms.

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:20.080
You don't want to compromise
your information architecture.

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:21.800
You don't want to have to choose
a completely different

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:24.240
information architecture
just for Android.

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:27.300
So when you look at Android,
don't think of it as designing

00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:28.490
a completely separate app.

00:19:28.490 --> 00:19:31.210
It's really how do I map
my existing information

00:19:31.210 --> 00:19:34.350
architecture, my existing
entities, the objects I deal

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:37.190
with, the sibling relationships
of things.

00:19:37.190 --> 00:19:39.430
How do you map those
onto Android?

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:42.020
So it's really, in this case,
with the information

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:44.500
architecture portion of the
design process, you really

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:45.930
have to think about,
how do I best

00:19:45.930 --> 00:19:48.690
communicate my existing content?

00:19:48.690 --> 00:19:51.340
My current content, and
manifest it in an

00:19:51.340 --> 00:19:53.061
Android-friendly way.

00:19:53.061 --> 00:19:55.330
NICK BUTCHER: So if you take a
look at the example of Gmail,

00:19:55.330 --> 00:19:58.010
for example. a product which
has existed on the web and

00:19:58.010 --> 00:20:01.480
elsewhere long before
Android came along.

00:20:01.480 --> 00:20:03.900
Android does not dictate
anything at all about this.

00:20:03.900 --> 00:20:06.200
Obviously using some Android
interaction patterns and

00:20:06.200 --> 00:20:08.730
visual design here, but the
information architecture,

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:12.230
there are basically messages,
conversations,

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:13.490
labels, and so forth.

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:17.270
This is purely dictated by
the product, by Gmail.

00:20:17.270 --> 00:20:19.150
So Android has no
bearing here.

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:21.080
ROMAN NURIK: It's very important
to make sure that

00:20:21.080 --> 00:20:24.180
when a user comes from the web
to Gmail, not that they

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:26.230
immediately see the
same exact things.

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:29.660
Like you don't want them to see
the exact same visuals.

00:20:29.660 --> 00:20:34.150
Maybe not even necessarily the
exact same ordering of

00:20:34.150 --> 00:20:36.490
content, but you do generally
want them to immediately

00:20:36.490 --> 00:20:41.030
understand where things are and
that all the things that

00:20:41.030 --> 00:20:42.776
they expect to be
there are there.

00:20:42.776 --> 00:20:45.390
NICK BUTCHER: Right.

00:20:45.390 --> 00:20:48.190
So the next slice we're
looking at is

00:20:48.190 --> 00:20:50.000
the interaction design.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:53.420
So here we'd say that it is
actually more important to get

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:57.655
a lot closer to Holo and to the
Android design patterns

00:20:57.655 --> 00:21:01.500
than to anything
really bespoke.

00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:04.700
The reason being that while
users might know your brand,

00:21:04.700 --> 00:21:07.380
and so on, when you're in the
context of the mobile device--

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:11.200
When I'm on my Android phone and
I'm using multiple apps,

00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:14.180
it's very important that your
application works the same way

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:16.380
as the rest of those
applications that are going to

00:21:16.380 --> 00:21:18.430
be used side by side.

00:21:18.430 --> 00:21:20.390
So this is where, I think,
interaction patterns such as

00:21:20.390 --> 00:21:22.800
navigation are really,
really critical.

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:26.200
That a user instantly knows how
to use your application.

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:30.090
Some users will have multiple
devices, maybe different OSs.

00:21:30.090 --> 00:21:33.500
I might use the website for one
thing and the phone for

00:21:33.500 --> 00:21:34.280
something else.

00:21:34.280 --> 00:21:39.600
But in our research and
experience, users tend to do a

00:21:39.600 --> 00:21:42.240
context switch when they switch
between these devices.

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:45.850
So I don't expect an application
on an Android

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:47.710
phone to function exactly
like the website.

00:21:47.710 --> 00:21:49.945
I expect it to function
like an Android app.

00:21:49.945 --> 00:21:51.950
And I kind of expect
that to happen.

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:55.030
And one point we wanted to
make is that bespoke

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:57.660
interactions, which keep your
brand defined, that's

00:21:57.660 --> 00:21:59.200
absolutely OK.

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:02.320
But if you do have an
interaction which is at odds

00:22:02.320 --> 00:22:05.000
with the Android design
patterns, it's working out

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.209
where it makes sense to back off
and where it makes sense

00:22:07.209 --> 00:22:09.061
to do something more bespoke.

00:22:09.061 --> 00:22:11.590
ROMAN NURIK: As an example kind
of outside of the mobile

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:18.140
context, on the web you have the
full breadth of HTML and

00:22:18.140 --> 00:22:21.820
CSS and styling and stuff
to communicate

00:22:21.820 --> 00:22:23.070
your content, right?

00:22:23.070 --> 00:22:25.030
But almost every website,
at the top

00:22:25.030 --> 00:22:26.890
left, they have a logo.

00:22:26.890 --> 00:22:28.930
Their navigation is either
at the top or

00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:30.080
along the left side.

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:31.790
And that's really just something
that's in the

00:22:31.790 --> 00:22:35.390
culture and in the core
of the web, right?

00:22:35.390 --> 00:22:36.980
So people kind of expect that.

00:22:36.980 --> 00:22:39.950
So that's the something where
you want to take your

00:22:39.950 --> 00:22:41.630
information architecture,
your content.

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:43.370
You're going to bring it to the
web, but you want to make

00:22:43.370 --> 00:22:46.380
that you use interactions
that are well

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:49.440
understood on the web.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:50.660
And it's the same thing
on Android.

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:52.770
So you really want to make sure
that when you come to a

00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:54.490
platform you bring your stuff.

00:22:54.490 --> 00:22:55.930
You bring your luggage
and stuff.

00:22:55.930 --> 00:22:59.560
But you put it into the right
parts of the house,

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:01.288
effectively.

